## Zambia
De 1962 – Northern Rhodesia's transition to independence. 
The 1962 constitution introduces African majority representation; 1964 elections bring Kaunda's UNIP to power; Zambia becomes independent. V2x 0.04 → 0.31.

Au 1968 – Kaunda consolidates one-party rule. 
The 1973 Choma declaration makes UNIP the sole legal party. V2x declines from ~0.31 → ~0.19.

De 1990 – Kaunda legalizes opposition under domestic protest pressure. 
The 1991 election brings Chiluba and the MMD to power, ending 27 years of one-party rule. V2x rises 0.19 → 0.49.

Au 2010 – Under Sata (2011) and Lungu (2015–2021): crackdown on opposition, closing of private media, politicization of the judiciary, and controversial constitutional changes. V2x falls 0.51 → 0.32.

De2018 – Civil society resistance to Lungu builds. 
The 2021 election brings Hichilema (HH) to power in a landmark democratic turnover. V2x recovers from ~0.32 → ~0.52.

## Venezuela
De 1936 – After the death of dictator Juan Vicente Gómez (1935), a democratic opening begins. 
The 1945 Revolution brings Acción Democrática to power; the 1947 election — Venezuela's first free election — elects Rómulo Gallegos. V2x 0.02 → 0.37.

Au 1948 – Military coup overthrows Gallegos. 
Pérez Jiménez establishes a brutal dictatorship (1948–1958).

De 1958 – The Punto Fijo Pact between major parties, after the overthrow of Pérez Jiménez, establishes stable two-party democracy (1958–1998). 
Betancourt returns to power. V2x surges 0.09 → 0.65.

Au 1998 – Chávez elected president. 
The 1999 constitution concentrates power in the presidency. Escalating repression: media muzzled (RCTV closed, 2007), Supreme Court packed, National Assembly neutralized. After Chávez's death (2013), Maduro deepens authoritarianism: 2017 Constituent Assembly supplants the elected legislature, economic collapse, overt repression, and mass emigration. V2x collapses 0.73 → 0.18.

## India
De 1950 – Constitution adopted (Jan 26, 1950). 
India becomes a sovereign democratic republic with universal suffrage. The 1951–52 general election — the world's largest democratic exercise at the time. V2x 0.27 → 0.60.

Au 1970 – Indira Gandhi's government grows increasingly authoritarian: the 1971 war popularity, economic crisis, mass protests (Nav Nirman, Bihar). 
The peak is the 1975–1977 Emergency: press censorship, arrests of 100,000+ opponents, suspension of civil liberties.

De 1976 – Gandhi calls elections in 1977 and is defeated by the Janata Party. Democracy restored, civil liberties reinstated. V2x recovers 0.38 → 0.65.
Au 2008 – Narendra Modi's BJP government: the 2014 election begins a period of democratic backsliding. Attacks on opposition (arrest of Kejriwal, Gandhi conviction), media repression, politicization of the judiciary, CAA/NRC protests (2019–2020), erosion of secular institutions, crackdown on civil society and NGOs. V2x declines 0.72 → 0.38.

## Germany
De 1918 – November Revolution at the end of WWI overthrows the monarchy. 
The Weimar Republic establishes a democratic constitution (1919) with universal suffrage (including women), proportional representation, and a bill of rights. V2x 0.25 → 0.64.

Au 1922 – The Weimar Republic's weaknesses (Article 48 emergency powers, Reichstag fragmentation) combined with the rise of Nazism. 
Key markers: Hitler's Beer Hall Putsch (1923), the Nazi electoral breakthrough (1930, 107 seats), Hitler appointed Chancellor (1933), the Reichstag Fire and Enabling Act (1933) dismantling democratic institutions, the Night of Long Knives (1934), and the Nuremberg Laws (1935). V2x plummets 0.64 → 0.07 by 1936.

No further episodes — post-WWII West Germany (Grundgesetz, 1949) and reunified Germany maintain consistently high v2x (~0.83–0.90) through the present.


## Mexico
De 1916 – The Mexican Revolution (1910–1920) culminates in the 1917 Constitution, establishing land reform, labor rights, and universal suffrage. 
Carranza's Constitutionalist faction prevails. V2x 0.11 → 0.23.

De 1988 – End of 71 years of PRI dominance begins. 
The 1988 election is marred by fraud (the "system crash"), triggering decades of electoral reform: 1990, 1993, 1994, 1996 reforms create an independent electoral authority (IFE/INE). The Zapatista uprising (1994) demands indigenous rights and democracy. The PRI loses its congressional majority in 1997. The historic 2000 election brings Vicente Fox (PAN) to the presidency. V2x rises 0.35 → 0.71.

Au 2020 – AMLO (president 2018–2024) and successor Claudia Sheinbaum: attacks on independent regulatory agencies, austerity for the judiciary and INE (electoral institute), concentration of executive power, and weakening of checks and balances. V2x falls 0.66 → 0.50.
